ðŸ”¹A tuple in Swift is a lightweight collection of multiple values grouped together into a single compound value.
 Tuples are useful when you want to return multiple values from a function or temporarily store related pieces of data without creating a full-fledged structure or class.

ðŸ”¹Declaring a Tuple
 let person = ("Aman", 25, true)

ðŸ”¹Accessing Tuple Elements
âœ… Using Indexes
print(person.0) // Output: Aman
print(person.1) // Output: 25
print(person.2) // Output: true

âœ… Using Named Elements
let personInfo = (name: "Aman", age: 25, isDeveloper: true)
print(personInfo.name)       // Output: Aman
print(personInfo.age)        // Output: 25
print(personInfo.isDeveloper) // Output: true

ðŸ”¹ Returning Multiple Values Using Tuples
func getUserInfo() -> (String, Int, Bool) {
    return ("Aman", 25, true)
}

let user = getUserInfo()
print("Name: \(user.0), Age: \(user.1), Developer: \(user.2)")
// Output: Name: Aman, Age: 25, Developer: true

ðŸ”¹ Tuple Destructuring (Decomposition)
let (name, age, isDeveloper) = person
print(name)        // Output: Aman
print(age)         // Output: 25
print(isDeveloper) // Output: true

